Although analyzing different answers, stories and memories, certain patterns were mentioned repeatedly. After reading through different replies and discussing repetitions and patterns, we coded the answers into the following 11, nonexclusive categories:


‘Social experiences’, when relationships to other players, friends and families (online and offline) were essential;



‘Single player’, when the experience focused on the single-player mode;



‘Victory’, whether winning was the core of the activity;



‘Narrative’, when the response included a specific narrative explaining a situation in the sport game; 



‘Mastery’, when the player mentioned his/her skills developed in the game as specifically meaningful;



‘Online’, whether the gameplay focused on online usage;



‘Passion’, whether the players mention their passion for a particular game; 



‘Personal connection’, whether the reported story included a particular subjective framing of the play experience; 



‘User-generated content’, whether the significance of the experience was related to user-generated content, such as character design and development or creating new teams; 



‘Mix real and virtual’, when the connection to real sport events or players was central;



‘Lack of meaningfulness’, whether the response neglected to answer or criticized the question.

Most answers included combinations of categories and 1996 category codes were assigned to the answers with an average of 2.07 categories per reply. By comparison, the graph shown in Figure 9 demonstrates the central patterns found in the players answers.
